<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41094a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41094a">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41094a"> 94(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> triple kingdom / min. veg. ani. / <font face="wake">G</font></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The three degrees of the human mind are strikingly presented to us in the <mark>three kingdoms</mark> of nature. The <mark>mineral</mark> kingdom, with its rocks, earths, minerals, fluids, and gases, stands for all that is inert and lifeless in human nature&mdash;mere knowledge, on the intellectual side, and animal instincts and propensities on the moral side. The <mark>vegetable</mark> kingdom, as we have seen, aptly typifies intellectual processes, a truth which is recognised in our everyday language. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The <mark>animal</mark> kingdom, as already stated, presents a series of expressive symbols, relating more especially to moral qualities. <small> George Trobridge, <a name="GTLS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#GTLS"><cite title="source">A Life of Emanuel Swedenborg</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (??) 176-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
